This lab provided practical experience with the full ROS 2 mobile-robot workflow: launching TurtleBot3 in Gazebo, visualizing live data in RViz, controlling the robot with teleop, recording topics with rosbag, generating a map with Cartographer, and implementing publisher/subscriber nodes for /cmd_vel and /odom. The main learning outcome was understanding how ROS 2 nodes, topics, TF frames, and simulation tools work together in a single navigation and mapping pipeline. A key challenge was handling differences between ideal commands and simulated behavior, including slight motion delay, drift, and odometry/map timing offsets. Another challenge was coordinating multiple terminals, launch files, and topic checks while keeping the system synchronized (use_sim_time, correct model/environment setup). Overall, the session built confidence in debugging robot behavior through topic inspection and RViz plugins, and established a strong foundation for future SLAM and autonomous navigation tasks.
